Feature Engineering: Earning Your Keep as a Data Scientist

Cornerstone #3 - Real-Estate Tycoon

"Feature engineering is difficult, time-intensive, requires expert knowledge." Let's see why.

The following Coding Section is a core part of this module. After watching the video above, please follow along inside your Companion Workbook. Try to implement each piece of code on your own. You will also find exercises at the end of your Companion Workbook, which are meant to be completed AFTER the coding section.

 

I. Leverage Domain Knowledge¶

You can often engineer informative features by tapping into your (or others') expertise about the domain. Try to think of specific information you might want to isolate. In fact, here's where you also have a lot of "creative freedom" to think of ideas for new features.

 

First, let's import the libraries we'll need.¶

In [1]:
# NumPy for numerical computing
import numpy as np

# Pandas for DataFrames
import pandas as pd
pd.set_option('display.max_columns', 100)
# pd.options.mode.chained_assignment = None  # default='warn'

# Matplotlib for visualization
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
# display plots in the notebook
%matplotlib inline 

# Seaborn for easier visualization
import seaborn as sns
sns.set_style('darkgrid')

# Load cleaned dataset from the previous module
df = pd.read_csv('cleaned_df.csv')

Example: 2 Beds & 2 Baths¶

For example, let's say that homes with 2 bedrooms and 2 bathrooms are especially popular for investors. Maybe you suspect these types of properties command premium prices.

Sure, the number of bedrooms and the number of bathrooms are both existing features in your dataset. However, they do not specifically isolate this property type. Therefore, to isolate them, you could create an indicator variable just for properties with 2 beds and 2 baths.

 

Boolean masks will help us perform feature engineering.¶

Here's how:

  • First, create a boolean mask to check for 2 beds
((df.beds == 2) & (df.baths == 2)).astype(int)
  • Then, create a boolean mask to check for 2 bathrooms
((df.beds == 2) & (df.baths == 2)).astype(int)
  • Next, combine the two masks with an & operator
((df.beds == 2) & (df.baths == 2)).astype(int)
  • Finally, convert the resulting series to type int to map from True/False to 1/0
((df.beds == 2) & (df.baths == 2)).astype(int)

Let's create that variable:

In [3]:
# Create indicator variable for properties with 2 beds and 2 baths
df['two_and_two'] = ((df.beds == 2) & (df.baths == 2)).astype(int)
 

Mean of an Indicator Variable¶

One side benefit from indicator variables is the ability to quickly check the proportion of our observations that meet the condition. Because 'two_and_two' contains only values of 1/0, we can take the mean to find the proportion of observations that have 2 beds and 2 baths.

In [4]:
# Display percent of rows where two_and_two == 1
print( df.two_and_two.mean() )
 
0.09458023379383634
 

Almost 9.5% of the transactions in our dataset were for properties with 2 beds and 2 baths.

 

Example: Housing Market Recession¶

Because we're modeling housing prices in the United States, it's important to consider the housing market recession. According to data from Zillow, the lowest housing prices were from 2010 to end of 2013 (country-wide).

Screenshot taken from Zillow Home Values

You could create an indicator feature for that. Here's how:

  1. Create a boolean mask to check if tx_year >= 2010
  2. Create a boolean mask to check if tx_year <= 2013
  3. Combine the two masks with an & operator
  4. Convert the resulting series to type int to map from True/False to 1/0

We'll do that in the exercises.

 

II. Create Interaction Features¶

In the first step, you engineered features from domain knowledge. However, "domain knowledge" is very broad and open-ended. At some point, you'll get stuck or exhaust your ideas.

That's where these next few steps come in. These are a few specific heuristics that can help spark more ideas. The first of these heuristics is checking to see if you can create any interaction features that make sense.

Interaction features are operations between two or more other features.¶

By the way, we mean this term pretty loosely. In some contexts, "interaction terms" must be products of two variables. However, in our context, interaction features can be products, sums, or differences between two features.

 

Example: Property Age¶

For example, in our dataset, we know the transaction year and the year the property was built in. However, just knowing the year built alone is not so useful, unless we suspect that all the houses built in a particular year were defective or subject to some other freak incident.

Instead, the more useful piece of information these two features provides is the age of the property at the time of the transaction. So let's create a 'property_age' feature.

In [5]:
# Create a property age feature
df['property_age'] = df.tx_year - df.year_built
 

It's always nice to do a quick sanity check after creating a feature. It could save you headaches down the road.

For example, 'property_age' should never be less than 0, right?

In [6]:
# Should not be less than 0
print( df.property_age.min() )
 
-8
 

Crap. Ok, something's going on... let's investigate.

 

Let's print the number of observations with 'property_age' less than 0.¶

  • First we'll create a boolean mask for our desired condition
sum(df.property_age < 0)
  • Then, we'll take the sum of the mask
sum(df.property_age < 0)

This will give us the total number of observations that meet our conditon:

In [7]:
# Number of observations with 'property_age' < 0
print( sum(df.property_age < 0) )
 
19
 

Ok, so not that many. On second thought, it's possible that some homeowners bought houses before the construction company built them. This is reasonable, especially with single-family homes. However, for our original problem, we are only interested in houses that already exist because our client only buys existing ones.

In the exercises, we'll do a quick pinch of ad-hoc data cleaning and remove these observations from our dataset.

 

III. Group Sparse Classes¶

The next heuristic we'll consider is grouping sparse classes in our categorical features.

Sparse classes are classes in categorical features that have very few total observations.¶

They can be problematic for certain machine learning algorithms, so we want to reduce the number of sparse classes in our categorical features.

  • At best, they are ignored.
  • At worst, they can cause models to be overfit.

Let's begin by plotting the bar plots for 'exterior_walls' again.

In [8]:
# Bar plot for exterior_walls
sns.countplot(y='exterior_walls', data=df)
plt.show()
 
 

As you can see, we have severals classes with very few observations. Let's consider ways we can group them.

 

To begin, we can start by grouping classes that are similar.¶

  • For example, we can group 'Wood Siding', 'Wood Shingle', and 'Wood' together.
  • In fact, let's just label all of them as 'Wood'.

Again, we can use .replace() function for this purpose.¶

  • First, we selected the feature that we want and call the .replace() function
df.exterior_walls.replace(['Wood Siding', 'Wood Shingle'], 'Wood', inplace=True)
  • Then, for the first argument, we passed in a list of class names to replace.
df.exterior_walls.replace(['Wood Siding', 'Wood Shingle'], 'Wood', inplace=True)
  • For the second argument, we passed in the new name to replace them with.
df.exterior_walls.replace(['Wood Siding', 'Wood Shingle'], 'Wood', inplace=True)
  • Finally, we told Pandas to replace the values in the original Series instead of making a copy of it
df.exterior_walls.replace(['Wood Siding', 'Wood Shingle'], 'Wood', inplace=True)
In [9]:
# Group 'Wood Siding' and 'Wood Shingle' with 'Wood'
df.exterior_walls.replace(['Wood Siding', 'Wood Shingle'], 'Wood', inplace=True)
 

Next, we can group remaining sparse classes into a single 'Other' class.¶

Let's label

  • 'Stucco'
  • 'Other'
  • 'Asbestos shingle'
  • 'Concrete Block', and
  • 'Masonry'

as 'Other':

In [10]:
# List of classes to group
other_exterior_walls = ['Concrete Block', 'Stucco', 'Masonry', 'Other', 'Asbestos shingle']

# Group other classes into 'Other'
df.exterior_walls.replace(other_exterior_walls, 'Other', inplace=True)
 

New Class Distributions¶

Finally, now that we've grouped together sparse classes, let's look at that bar plot again.

In [11]:
# Bar plot for exterior_walls
sns.countplot(y='exterior_walls', data=df)
plt.show()
 
 

Great. It looks like each of the remaining classes have a decent number of observations.

  • There's no formal rule of how many each class needs.
  • It also depends on the size of your dataset and the number of other features you have.
  • As a rule of thumb, we recommend combining classes until the each one has at least around 50 observations.

In the exercises, we'll give the 'roof' feature the same treatment.

 

IV. Prepare Analytical Base Table¶

Before we move on, we'll need to finalize the table to use for modeling. In other words, this is the table that has already been cleaned and augmented through feature engineering, and we'll be performing our analyses or building our models on it. Therefore, we'll call it the analytical base table (ABT).

Dummy Variables¶

Python machine learning algorithms cannot handle categorical features directly. Specifically, they cannot handle text data. Therefore, we need to create what are called dummy variables for our categorical features.

For example, for the 'exterior_walls' feature (after grouping sparse classes), we're left with 8 unique classes:¶

  1. 'Wood'
  2. 'Brick'
  3. 'Other'
  4. 'Siding (Alum/Vinyl)'
  5. 'Missing'
  6. 'Metal'
  7. 'Brick veneer'
  8. 'Combination'
In [12]:
print( df.exterior_walls.unique() )
 
['Wood' 'Brick' 'Other' 'Siding (Alum/Vinyl)' 'Missing' 'Metal'
 'Brick veneer' 'Combination']
 

And right now, they are encoded as text values in a single feature column:

In [13]:
# Display first 5 values of 'exterior_walls'
df.exterior_walls.head()
Out[13]:
0     Wood
1    Brick
2     Wood
3     Wood
4    Brick
Name: exterior_walls, dtype: object
 

Dummy variables are binary (0 or 1) features that each represent a single class from a categorical feature.¶

  • The information you're representing is exactly the same, but this allows you to run machine learning algorithms on your dataset.

So in the 'exterior_walls' example, we would create 8 new dummy variables, one for each of its unique classes:

  1. 'exterior_walls_Wood'
  2. 'exterior_walls_Brick'
  3. 'exterior_walls_Other'
  4. 'exterior_walls_Siding (Alum/Vinyl)'
  5. 'exterior_walls_Missing'
  6. 'exterior_walls_Metal'
  7. 'exterior_walls_Brick veneer'
  8. 'exterior_walls_Combination'

So if an observation had exterior walls made of 'Brick', it would have the following values for the dummy variables:¶

  1. 'exterior_walls_Wood' = 0
  2. 'exterior_walls_Brick' = 1
  3. 'exterior_walls_Other' = 0
  4. 'exterior_walls_Siding (Alum/Vinyl)' = 0
  5. 'exterior_walls_Missing' = 0
  6. 'exterior_walls_Metal' = 0
  7. 'exterior_walls_Brick veneer' = 0
  8. 'exterior_walls_Combination' = 0
 

Thankfully, Pandas has an incredibly easy function for doing this automatically.¶

  • It's called pd.get_dummies().
  • Tip: Scroll to the right in the table below and look at the 8 new dummy variables created for 'exterior_walls'.
In [14]:
# Get dummy variables and display first 5 observations
pd.get_dummies( df, columns=['exterior_walls'] ).head()

Important: Note that...

pd.get_dummies( df.head(), columns=['exterior_walls'] )

...would NOT be correct, as Pandas would then only use the first 5 observations to create the dummy variables. So if the first 5 observations only had 2 unique classes for the feature, then Pandas would only create 2 dummy variables.

In the exercises, we'll create and save dummy variables for all of our categorical features.

 

Finally, let's remove unused or redundant features from our dataset.

Unused features are those that won't go into our machine learning algorithms.¶

Common examples of unused features include:

  • ID columns
  • Features that wouldn't be available (e.g. price of the property 5 years after the transaction)
  • Other text descriptions or metadata

For this dataset, we don't have any unused features.

 

Redundant features would typically be those that have been replaced by other features that you've added.¶

For example, since we used 'tx_year' and 'year_built' to create the 'property_age' feature, we might consider removing them.

  • Removing 'tx_year' could also be a good idea because we don't want our model being overfit to the transaction year, since we'll be applying it to properties in the future.
  • In other words, we want the model to focus on learning patterns from the other features.

In the exercises, we'll remove those features using Pandas's .drop() function.

 

Finally, we'll need to save the analytical base table.¶

Before we move on to the next module, we'll need save the augmented dataframe with all our new features. Remember to complete this step in the exercises for this module!

 

Final Tip: No Such Thing as Perfect¶

Not all of the features you engineer need to be winners. In fact, you'll often find that many of them do not add much value to your model.

That's OK!

One highly predictive feature makes up for 10 duds. The key is choosing machine learning algorithms that can effectively select the best features among many options (built-in feature selection). This will allow you to avoid overfitting your model despite providing many input features. We'll cover this in the next module!
